06:15.760 --> 06:17.342
all. What factors were involved in your decision 
to go to Texas A&M as opposed to, say, some other

06:19.634 --> 06:26.082
school? I think one thing was I understood that it 
didn't cost as much as some other schools. And also

06:33.072 --> 06:46.249
there was a man named Sawyer

06:33.072 --> 06:46.249
who was, I believe, an 1870-some-odd

06:33.072 --> 06:46.249
graduate or student. at A&M who lived in the 
country. And his son, several years older than I,

06:49.380 --> 06:56.686
had gone there also. And another boy named Edwin 
Patterson and myself decided we would go down and

06:58.588 --> 07:08.376
become electrical engineers. We'd been fooling 
around with radio and the old dot dash sort of stuff

07:16.823 --> 07:26.518
and thought that we'd go down there and become 
electrical engineers. He did, but I didn't. I

07:29.102 --> 07:30.784
noted that you were in architecture. Yes. I 
switched to architecture after my first year and

07:31.966 --> 07:39.358
found out that there was so much math in the regular 
engineering course. What procedures did you go

07:41.060 --> 07:44.265
through to enter Texas A&M? we got a catalog and 
found out how many units I believe they called it in

07:46.777 --> 08:14.623
those days of high school work you had to have to 
enter and I believe I just barely had enough

07:46.777 --> 08:14.623
because we we only had 11 grades in high school at 
that time and

07:46.777 --> 08:14.623
I recall going to the superintendent of our high 
school and asking him to

08:15.599 --> 08:27.361
support me in my efforts to go there, and he did. 
Yeah, I think he wrote a letter or something like

08:27.701 --> 08:30.106
that. Our high school wasn't the best in the world, 
I guess, but maybe we learned some things that they

08:31.689 --> 08:39.042
don't learn now. I believe there was a period, and 
it probably was during the time that you entered

08:39.325 --> 08:53.327
A&M, that there were schools that were so-called 
affiliated with A&M, and if you completed one of

08:39.325 --> 08:53.327
those, then you could be accepted without an 
entrance exam. Well, I did not take an entrance

08:53.888 --> 09:00.338
exam, but I don't know whether we were affiliated 
or not. But anyway, the letter that he wrote, I got

09:00.358 --> 09:07.729
entrance there. There weren't so many students 
trying to go there then. What were your first

09:11.120 --> 09:18.068
reactions to Texas A&M and to what there was of the 
community of College Station when you arrived?

09:21.091 --> 09:23.433
I hardly know. Of course, I was lonesome. I was 
barely 17 years old. And

09:28.959 --> 09:37.969
there was a little hazing going on even before 
registration.

09:40.463 --> 09:50.258
like

09:40.463 --> 09:50.258
pushing a cart with the trunks for the old boys up 
from the station. And I was a little bit disturbed,

09:50.338 --> 09:56.046
I think, long about that time. So there were some 
upperclassmen who arrived, I presume, on the same

09:56.066 --> 10:00.092
train with you? On the same train with

10:00.112 --> 10:04.639
myself. Were there any people there to meet the 
train when it arrived? I don't believe so. Perhaps

10:11.456 --> 10:15.480
they might have been, but I just don't recall that. 
But a boy named Horace Sawyer was a freshman coming

10:16.181 --> 10:33.220
in, and I believe he's one of your distinguished 
men of the school now, and a boy named E.B.

10:33.260 --> 10:37.825
Patterson, who is now dead, the three of us. And 
then there were several older students, former

10:38.210 --> 10:53.910
students, old students, arrived on the same 
train, and we got a little hazing on the train

10:38.210 --> 10:53.910
itself, I believe. We had to do a little singing for 
them, such as that, but that was all right. Okay.

